The initial doubt was
{quote}
I deleted my initial projects to start over, created a new project, and when I go in to administer this newly created project, the summary screen does not match what I see in the documentation.

For instance, I only have a settings and tabs tile on the right side of the page, no issue types, people, workflows, versions, etc.

I must be doing something wrong but I feel like this page showed up correctly for the projects I tried before deleting and starting over.
{quote}

Studio can start quite a few executors to perform so delayed work. However, it does not shutdown these executors if data inside of JIRA is restored. This can leave the Executors either calling out of date managers which results in exceptions and memory leaks. We need to shutdown any long running tasks before a JIRA data restore.

For example, consider JiraApplicationEnabledListener.notifyApplicationEnabledEvent. If the call to the remote project fails it does this happens:

{code}
inal ScheduledExecutorService executorService = Executors.newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor(new CustomizableThreadFactory(newlyEnabledApplication.getDisplayName() + "-project-sync"));

executorService.scheduleWithFixedDelay(new Runnable()
{
  @Override
  public void run()
  {
    if (extendProjectsToApplication(newlyEnabledApplication))
    {
        executorService.shutdown();
    }
  }
}, getRetryIntervalInSeconds(), getRetryIntervalInSeconds(), TimeUnit.SECONDS);
{code}

If JIRA is restore without the project being "extended" it will continue to call {{extendProjectsToApplication()}} on a service that is no longer current. In this case it will cause a whole bunch of exceptions in the logs until JIRA is restarted.

If you give a group 'Commit' permissions on the root SVN path (secure/admin/PathRepositoryPermissions.jspa?svnPath=/), and then try to give the same group 'read' access for a particular project path (https://androidplot.jira.com/secure/admin/ProjectRepositoryPermissions.jspa?repositoryKey=<PATH>), the studio UI will list the group as having 'Commit' access.

The SVN authz file will be updated correctly, so the group will not actually have commit access, but the UI will be misleading.

SVN authz file contents are here - you can see that developers group has 'rw' permissions for '/' and 'r' permissions for 'ANDROIDPLOT'. But the attached screenshots display that 'developers' has Commit access to 'ANDROIDPLOT'.
{noformat}
[asrinivasan@androidplot conf]$ cat /data/jirastudio/svn/root/conf/authz
[groups]
developers = 
administrators = 
_no-one-at-all = 
users = 
trusted-developers = 
balsamiq-mockups-editors = 
confluence-administrators = 
trusted-users = 
[/]
@developers = rw
@administrators = rw
@_no-one-at-all = r
@users = r
_bamboo-svn-user = r
[/ANDROIDPLOT]
* = r
@users = 
@trusted-developers = rw
@administrators = rw
@developers = r
@_no-one-at-all = r
@balsamiq-mockups-editors = r
{noformat}

To find the offending Gadgets the following query can be issued on the database:
{code}
select * from portletconfiguration where gadget_xml IS NULL;
{code}

